# CSV Parser - Practical Examples

## Table of Contents
1. [Basic Parsing](#basic-parsing)
2. [Working with Quoted Fields](#working-with-quoted-fields)
3. [Custom Delimiters](#custom-delimiters)
4. [Type Coercion](#type-coercion)
5. [Error Handling](#error-handling)
6. [Filtering Data](#filtering-data)
7. [Aggregation Methods](#aggregation-methods)
8. [Real-World Scenarios](#real-world-scenarios)

---

## Basic Parsing

### Example 1: Parse Simple CSV
```typescript
import { parseCSV } from "./csv-parser";

const csv = `id,name,email
1,John Doe,john@example.com
2,Jane Smith,jane@example.com
3,Bob Johnson,bob@example.com`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(result.headers);
// Output: ["id", "name", "email"]

console.log(result.rows);
// Output: [
//   { id: 1, name: "John Doe", email: "john@example.com" },
//   { id: 2, name: "Jane Smith", email: "jane@example.com" },
//   { id: 3, name: "Bob Johnson", email: "bob@example.com" }
// ]
```

### Example 2: Access Individual Fields
```typescript
const firstRow = result.rows[0];
console.log(firstRow.name); // "John Doe"
console.log(firstRow.email); // "john@example.com"

// Iterate through all rows
for (const row of result.rows) {
  console.log(`${row.name} (${row.email})`);
}
```

---

## Working with Quoted Fields

### Example 3: Handle Addresses with Commas
```typescript
const csv = `name,address,city
"Smith, John","123 Main St, Apt 4",NYC
"Doe, Jane","456 Oak Ave, Suite 200",LA`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(result.rows[0]);
// Output: {
//   name: "Smith, John",
//   address: "123 Main St, Apt 4",
//   city: "NYC"
// }
```

### Example 4: Handle Escaped Quotes
```typescript
const csv = `name,description
Product A,"This item ""rocks"" according to reviews"
Product B,"The brand says ""highest quality"""`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(result.rows[0].description);
// Output: This item "rocks" according to reviews

console.log(result.rows[1].description);
// Output: The brand says "highest quality"
```

### Example 5: Complex Quoted Fields
```typescript
const csv = `id,title,content
1,"Article: Programming","Learn ""advanced"" techniques, tips, and tricks"
2,"Guide: CSV Parsing","Handle ""quoted fields"", commas, and ""escapes"""`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

// All quotes are properly handled
console.log(result.rows[0].content);
// Output: Learn "advanced" techniques, tips, and tricks
```

---

## Custom Delimiters

### Example 6: Tab-Separated Values (TSV)
```typescript
const tsv = `product\tprice\tquantity
Widget\t9.99\t100
Gadget\t19.99\t50
Tool\t14.99\t75`;

const result = parseCSV(tsv, { delimiter: "\t" });

console.log(result.headers);
// Output: ["product", "price", "quantity"]

console.log(result.rows[0]);
// Output: { product: "Widget", price: 9.99, quantity: 100 }
```

### Example 7: Semicolon-Separated Values
```typescript
const csv = `name;department;salary
Alice;Engineering;80000
Bob;Sales;60000
Charlie;Marketing;65000`;

const result = parseCSV(csv, { delimiter: ";" });

console.log(result.rows);
// Output: [
//   { name: "Alice", department: "Engineering", salary: 80000 },
//   { name: "Bob", department: "Sales", salary: 60000 },
//   { name: "Charlie", department: "Marketing", salary: 65000 }
// ]
```

### Example 8: Pipe-Separated with Quoted Fields
```typescript
const csv = `name|address|phone
"Johnson, Mike"|"123 Main St, Apt 5"|555-1234
"Williams, Sarah"|"456 Oak Ave, Suite 100"|555-5678`;

const result = parseCSV(csv, { delimiter: "|" });

console.log(result.rows[0].address);
// Output: 456 Oak Ave, Suite 100
```

### Example 9: Custom Quote Character
```typescript
const csv = `text
'He said "Hello"'
'She replied "Hi there"'`;

const result = parseCSV(csv, { quote: "'" });

console.log(result.rows[0].text);
// Output: He said "Hello"
```

### Example 10: Windows Line Endings (CRLF)
```typescript
const csv = `name,age\r\nJohn,30\r\nJane,25`;

const result = parseCSV(csv, { lineSeparator: "\r\n" });

console.log(result.rows.length);
// Output: 2
```

